I am a PhD student at the University of Tennessee. My research goals are twofold:

1) Develop a highly general method for generating on-the-fly molecular dynamics potentials that are both fast and accurate by applying data science techniques (machine learning, kernel methods, etc.) to the results of slower but more accurate simulations (e.g., DFT or QMC).

2) Develop methods to extract archetypal atomic neighborhoods from novel materials. Experimental data describing these materials is obtained via atom probe tomography; however, the data is corrupted by a large amount of noise and missing information. Recent research in rank recovery and matrix completion (e.g., the Netflix problem) provides a way to reveal the underlying low-dimensional patterns that exist in the data in an unbiased way.

In order to test the effectiveness of these methods, I am using them to study the localization of lithium ions in novel carbon composite anodes developed at Oak Ridge National Laboratory. These anodes are both crystalline and amorphous, and thus the Li-ions diffuse and localize in highly non-obvious ways.
